<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Automakers Urge Minivehicle Standards Expansion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Automakers Urge Minivehicle Standards Expansion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504093994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0922 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1504093994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 15 KYODO -- Minivehicle manufacturers 
are seeking expansion of standards for minivehicles to improve 
their safety levels to those of regular-size vehicles, an 
industry association reported Friday [15 April]. 
  The Japan Automobile Manufacturers Association said the move 
was initiated by the association's special committee on 
minivehicles headed by Osamu Suzuki, president of Suzuki Motor 
Corp. 
  The association will formally decide on details of standard 
expansion, including the size of vehicles and maximum engine 
capacity, association officials said. 
  They said it is likely that the maximum engine capacity for 
minivehicles will be raised to 800 cc from the present 660 cc. 
  The Transport Ministry will launch a study on the 
modification of minivehicle standards after the committee comes 
up with a formal proposal, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

