<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-073 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul Withdraws Demand on Exchange of Envoys </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seoul Withdraws Demand on Exchange of Envoys </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1504015994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0152 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1504015994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 15 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean 
Government announced Friday it has decided to withdraw 
unconditionally its demand on an inter-Korean envoy exchange as 
a condition for Pyongyang to hold further high-level talks with 
Washington. 
  The decision represents a major concession by South Korea 
and 
the United States and will likely raise the pressure on North 
Korea to allow additional checks of its nuclear facilities. 
  The government also said it will accept all North Korean 
escapees from Pyongyang-run logging camps in Siberia wishing to 
settle here. 
  The deputy prime minister and head of the National 
Unification Board (NUB), Yi Yong-tok, made the announcement 
following a meeting of cabinet ministers concerned with 
reunification and national security policy. 
  "The government has determined that it was practically 
impossible to resolve the nuclear issue through an exchange of 
special envoys," since North Korea has clearly shown that it has 
no intention of doing so, he said. Consequently, the government 
has decided against pushing the envoy exchange as a condition 
for a third round of U.S.- North Korea high-level talks any 
longer, Yi explained. 
  "However, there is no change in the government's position 
that the nuclear problem will have to be resolved above 
everything else," he said. "Inter-Korean dialogue must go on for 
mutual and simultaneous inspections of each other's nuclear 
facilities based on the joint declaration for denuclearization 
of the Korean peninsula," Yi said. 
  The deputy prime minister added that IAEA [International 
Atomic Energy Agency] checks of North Korea's nuclear sites will 
also have to be realized soon. With regard to North Korean 
loggers, Yi said the government, based on humanitarian grounds, 
has decided to accept all escapees seeking asylum in the South 
after following the proper legal procedures. 
  Seoul has received a promise from the Russian Government on 
the matter, he said, adding that concerned South Korean 
ministries would take early steps to accept them. 
  Based on the decision, the government is expected to discuss 
a third round of U.S.-North Korean talks and other problems 
related to the nuclear issue when Robert Gallucci, U.S. 
assistant secretary of state for political and military affairs, 
arrives in Seoul Friday. 
  "The United States' talks with Pyongyang are linked with 
inter- Korean dialogue," Yi said. Therefore, any decisions on 
U.S.-North Korean negotiations will be made in close 
consultation between Washington and Seoul, Yi said. 
  The deputy prime minister, however, hinted that inter-Korean 
dialogue besides the special envoy exchange would not be a 
condition for the third round of U.S.-North Korean talks. 
  Meanwhile, the government is expected to hold a 
working-level 
meeting of Foreign Ministry, Chongwadae [presidential office] 
and National Unification Board officials Friday afternoon to 
discuss ways to accommodate North Korean loggers seeking asylum 
in the South. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5897 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas073_d_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-073 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC, Japan, Russia Welcome Exchange Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC, Japan, Russia Welcome Exchange Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1504053494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0527 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1504053494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 15 (YONHAP) -- China, Japan and Russia 
welcomed South Korea's flexibility when consulted beforehand 
about Seoul's decision to withdraw its demand for an 
inter-Korean envoy exchange, a Foreign Ministry official said 
Friday. 
  The decision, while aimed at turning the North Korean 
nuclear 
crisis away from international sanctions, would at the same time 
convince the world community including China that sanctions were 
inevitable if Pyongyang ignored even this incentive, the 
official said. 
  Seoul has attempted to break the nuclear impasse by saying 
it 
would no longer demand an inter-Korean envoy exchange as a 
precondition to North Korean-U.S. high-level talks. 
  The decision separates inter-Korean from North Korean-U.S. 
dialogue under Seoul's strategy to resolve the nuclear problem, 
leaving the issue to Pyongyang and Washington to untangle. 
  The North's recent behavior, such as threatening to turn 
Seoul into a "sea of fire," proved the South could not expect 
any progress in the nuclear dispute via an envoy exchange, the 
ministry official said. 
  "The decision to cut the link reflects the government's will 
to place prior emphasis on transparent inspection by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)," he said. 
  Washington was fully consulted about Seoul's move, he said, 
while China, Japan and Russia welcomed it, noted the official. 
  "If North Korea blocks progress on the inspection despite 
such efforts on our part, the international community will gain 
justification in seeking sanctions against it," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

