<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Bans Loggers in Siberia From Leaving Camp </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Bans Loggers in Siberia From Leaving Camp </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1504052994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0522 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1504052994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 15 (YONHAP) -- North Korea has 
prohibited its loggers working in Siberia from leaving or 
sleeping outside their camps, a Foreign Ministry official said 
Friday. 
  "North Korea permitted the loggers to go out and sleep on 
some special days in the past such as April 15, the birthday of 
President Kim Il-song, and Aug. 15, independence day from 
Japanese colonial rule, on a large scale. But this year the 
Pyongyang government banned it completely on April 15," the 
official said on condition he not be named. 
  North Korea seems to think that if Seoul admits defecting 
loggers to South Korea, more loggers will desert their camps. 
North Korean guards at the camps have thus increased 
surveillance of workers and banned movement to outside areas, 
the official said. 
  He expressed concern that North Korean loggers left camp in 
the past to buy daily necessities and food in Khabarovsk, but 
now they cannot do so. 

</TEXT>

