<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK-PRC Firm Plans ROK-DPRK Sea Route </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK-PRC Firm Plans ROK-DPRK Sea Route </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1504015294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0141 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1504015294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 15 (YONHAP) -- A regular, direct sea 
route between South and North Korea will open on April 18, 
business sources said Friday. 
  Sunho shipping company, a joint venture between South 
Korea's 
Samsun Shipping Corp. and China's Xianhu business group, has 
chartered a 4,200-ton containership from St. Vincent and the 
Grenadines and will send it from Pusan to the North Korean port 
of Chongjin on Monday. 
  The ship will carry 1,400 tons of construction equipment, 
which is to be transported again by truck from Chongjin to China. 
  The Pusan-Chongjin-Yanji route will shorten the time needed 
to transport goods to seven days, compared to the previous 40-45 
days on the Pusan-Dalian-Yanji route. 
  Sunho plans to operate ships on the route once a month on a 
regular basis, Samsun officials said. 
  The inter-Korean sea route became available after the Xianhu 
group contracted with the North Korean Government to jointly 
develop Chongjin port last June. Under the contract, the 
Chinese group has the right to use the port for 50 years. 
  Samsun opened a sea route from Inchon through a Chinese port 
to the North Korean port of Nampo early last year and is 
operating freighters on the route twice a month. 
  A Samsun official said, "if inter-Korean relations improve, 
goods transported through this direct inter-Korean sea route 
will also increase." 
  Samsun carried 5,000 tons of rice from Mokpo to the North 
Korean port of Najin in July 1991 -- a first for a Korean 
shipping company. 

</TEXT>

