<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Group's Unfair Trade Practice Study Cited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Group's Unfair Trade Practice Study Cited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1504011994 Seoul THE KOREA TIMES in English 15 Apr 94 p 9 </F>
<F P=103> SK1504011994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The United States has erected many non-tariff 
barriers on its imports although it has put pressure on foreign 
nations to rectify their unfair practices, the Korea Trade 
Promotion Corporation (KOTRA) said, quoting a report of a U.S. 
civilian body. 
  In a report on U.S. unfair trade practices, the Citizens for 
a Sound Economy Foundation said that there are many unfair 
practices in the United States and certain barriers are higher 
than those in foreign countries. 
  The report pointed out that the United States has set up 
complicated guidelines on automobile fuel efficiency which have 
become non-tariff import barriers on European deluxe cars. 
  The body claimed that the United States has limited imports 
of dairy products to 2 percent of total U.S. production and 
tariffs are high at 10-20 percent although it puts pressure on 
foreign countries to open their farm markets. 
  It also pinpointed non-tariff barriers in services, claiming 
that foreigners are strictly banned from engaging in TV and 
radio broadcasting business in the United States although U.S. 
operators have pressurized foreign governments to open their 
markets. 
  In the public construction works, foreigners are obligated 
to 
use U.S. made construction equipment and material under the Buy 
American Act. 
  The body pointed out that the Bill Clinton administration 
plans to increase subsidies to industries and agriculture 
despite Uruguay Round accord on reduction of subsidies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

