<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Resolution of PRC History Book Issue `Unlikely' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Resolution of PRC History Book Issue `Unlikely' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1504084294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0549 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1504084294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 15 (YONHAP) -- Wu Xueqian, vice 
chairman of the Chinese People's Political Consultative 
Conference, hinted at the possibility of revising the Chinese 
school textbooks that claim South Korea attacked the North to 
trigger the Korean war (1950-53) during his recent visit, but 
education authorities see little coming of it. 
  Since ties were normalized in August 1992, South Korean and 
Chinese textbook editors have discussed correcting inaccurate 
accounts of the other's country in school textbooks at several 
seminars, but failed to reach any agreement, Education Ministry 
officials said Friday. 
  One Chinese textbook reads: "A war erupted in Choson 
(Korea). 
American imperialists invaded the North." 
  Seoul wants it stated clearly that a Southward invasion took 
place, but Beijing is unwilling because it would mean China 
supported the invader. 
  The Chinese communists apparently wanted to assert they 
helped the North Koreans because a northward push by the 
Americans could have threatened their country, justifying their 
involvement in the war. 
  For Beijing's part, it wants Seoul to indicate that 
Manchuria 
belongs to its northeastern region and Taiwan is one of its 
provinces. 
  These disagreements make it unlikely that China will correct 
its textbooks anytime in the near future, officials here said. 
  The ministry, nonetheless, will continue to invite Chinese 
textbook editors to seminars and hold more discussions. 

</TEXT>

