Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials, Former Foreign Leaders Hold Talk </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials, Former Foreign Leaders Hold Talk </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1404232694 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1527 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1404232694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 14 (KCNA) -- Officials of the 
Reunification Policy Committee of the Supreme People's Assembly 
[SPA] had a roundtable talk with the visiting former heads of 
state and government and politicians of different countries here 
today. 
  Present there were Kim Yong-sun, secretary of the Central 
Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea and chairman of the 
Reunification Policy Committee of the SPA; Yi Chong-hyok, senior 
councillor of the Reunification Policy Committee of the SPA; and 
other officials concerned. 
  Also present were ex-president of Costa Rica Rodrigo Carazo 
Odio, former Governor-general of Canada Edward Schreyer, former 
Prime Minister of Egypt Aziz Sedky, former chief of staff of the 
Armed Forces of France, member of the European Parliament and 
Chairman of the Union of Independentists General of the Army 
Jeannou Lacaze, former member of the Parliament of France and 
member of the European Parliament Pierro Ceyrac, Senior 
Vice-president of the Center for Strategic and International 
Studies of the United States William Taylor, Senior 
Vice-president of the CNN International Eason Jordan, Executive 
Director of the Summit Council for World Peace Antonio 
Betancourt, Director of Research of the Summit Council for World 
Peace Mark P. Barry, former senior advisor to the assistant 
secretary of State for Human Rights of the United States James 
Zumwalt, managing editor of THE WASHINGTON TIMES Josette Shiner, 
Executive Director of WASHINGTON TIMES Photo Agency Victoria 
Yokota, President Hirooatsu Ota and Vice-president Togashi 
Takayoshi of the Summit Council for World Strategy of Japan and 
others. 
  They exchanged views on the situation of the Korean 
peninsula 
surrounding the nuclear issue, DPRK-U.S. relations, etc. 
  The Korean side said that to denuclearize the Korean 
peninsula was the consistent stand of the Democratic People's 
Republic of Korea and it had made persistent efforts to this 
end. It also said that the nuclear issue was a matter to be 
resolved between the DPRK and the United States. 
  It held that the DPRK-U.S. talks must be continued and the 
DPRK's stand for solving the nuclear issue and improving the 
DPRK- U.S. relations through dialogue was invariable. 
  It said that as the efforts of one side were not enough to 
resolve the matters, the United States, too, must approach the 
dialogue with faith and sincerity. 
  It stressed that the progress of the DPRK-U.S. talks 
depended entirely on the United States. 
  Referring to the question of national reunification, the 
Korean side declared that invariable was the DPRK's stand for 
reunifying the country independently and peacefully on the basis 
of great national unity. 
  It said that witnessing the reality of Korea at first hand, 
the guests might judge impartially who truly wanted peace and 
reunification and who sought war, confrontation and division. 
  The Korean side declared that the DPRK would invigorate the 
struggle for national reunification on the basis of unity of the 
whole nation under the banner of "10-point programme of the 
great unity of the whole nation for the reunification of the 
country" put forward by the great leader President Kim Il-song. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

