<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Defense Secretary Postpones Tokyo Trip </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Defense Secretary Postpones Tokyo Trip </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404235594 Tokyo KYODO in English 2302 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404235594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 14 KYODO -- Defense Secretary 
William Perry on Thursday [14 April] abruptly postponed a visit 
to South Korea and Japan planned for next week following the 
accidental downing of two U.S. helicopters by American jets over 
northern Iraq. 
  A Pentagon spokesman, Maj. Steve Little, said he does not 
know when Perry will be able to make the trip. 
  "We don't know yet how long it will be delayed. The 
scheduling is definitely a problem," little told KYODO NEWS 
SERVICE by phone. 
  The Pentagon issued a statement about the cancellation of 
Perry's trip hours after a senior Defense Department official 
briefed reporters on the upcoming visit, which would have been 
Perry's first to the region since becoming defense chief in 
early February. 
  "The decision (to postpone the trip) was made to allow 
Secretary Perry time to ensure that the families of those who 
were killed are fully supported, to guarantee a thorough 
investigation, and also to review the existing procedures," the 
Pentagon said. 
  Perry was originally scheduled to arrive in Seoul on Sunday 
and travel on to Tokyo on Tuesday before returning home on 
Thursday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5949 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas073_a_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-073 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Attends Dinner Hosted by Mondale </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hosokawa Attends Dinner Hosted by Mondale </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504144794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1422 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1504144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 15 KYODO -- Departing Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa and U.S. Ambassador to Japan Walter Mondale 
agreed Friday [15 April] to continue cooperating with each other 
in further enhancing ties between Japan and the United States. 
  The two reached the accord at a dinner party hosted by 
Mondale and his wife, Joan, at the U.S. envoy's official 
residence in central Tokyo, Hosokawa told reporters. Hosokawa's 
wife, Kayoko, also attended. 
  Mondale reportedly voiced regret over Hosokawa's decision to 
resign due to the Diet paralysis on the fiscal 1994 budget, 
which was spawned by allegations of his financial improprieties. 
  Mondale also called on Hosokawa to continue working with him 
after his resignation to further promote bilateral relations, 
the premier said. 
  Hosokawa, 56, who suddenly offered to step down last week, 
will remain on board until his successor is chosen. 
  Friday night's dinner party followed an earlier invitation 
from Hosokawa asking the Mondales to his official residence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5950 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas073_d_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-073 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Envoy Threatens NPT Withdrawal `Again' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Envoy Threatens NPT Withdrawal `Again' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1504010794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0041 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1504010794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 15 (YONHAP) -- North Korea has again 
threatened to pull out of the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty 
(NPT) should Washington continue pressuring Pyongyang over its 
nuclear development program. 
  North Korean Ambassador to Moscow Son Song-pil made the 
threat at a recent press meeting, saying the International 
Atomic Energy Agency's report on its "unsatisfactory" inspection 
of North Korea's facilities and the failed Pyongyang-Washington 
talks have heightened tension on the Korean peninsula, NAEWOE 
PRESS, Seoul's official North Korea watcher, reported Thursday 
in quoting Radio Moscow. 
  Washington has pressed for strong action and Pyongyang 
should 
now adopt countermeasures, Son was quoted as saying. North 
Korea "could carry out its decision to withdraw from the NPT 
last year." 
  Son reiterated that the nuclear dispute can be settled only 
through North Korean-U.S. dialogue, saying the American threat 
to use force poses a grave obstacle, NAEWOE reported. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

