<H3> <TI>   MOFA Spokesman Backs ROK Call for N-S Dialogue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MOFA Spokesman Backs ROK Call for N-S Dialogue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1804083894 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 16 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1804083894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ministry of Foreign Affairs [MOFA] spokesman 
Terusuke Terada issued a statement on 15 April supporting the 
South Korean policy which was announced by Yi Yong-tok, deputy 
prime minister and concurrently chief of the National 
Unification Board, on the same day in connection with North 
Korea's (DPRK's) suspected nuclear weapon development. In 
announcing the policy, Deputy Prime Minister Yi stated that 
South Korea would not seek the exchange of special envoys 
between South Korea and North Korea any more, and called for 
South-North dialogue to pave the way for implementing mutual 
inspections of their military facilities. 
  In his statement, spokesman Terada said: "We highly 
appreciate the policy because it aims at promoting dialogue 
between South and North and seeking a solution to the situation 
through such dialogue, in line with a presidential statement 
issued by the UN Security Council." 

</TEXT>

