<DOCNO> FBIS4-6096 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas074__a94029" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-074-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 April 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ, DSP Oppose Watanabe Joining Coalition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ, DSP Oppose Watanabe Joining Coalition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504022994 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 15 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1504022994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 15 April Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Tomiichi Murayama, chairman of the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan [SDPJ], and Keigo Ouchi, chairman of the 
Democratic Socialist Party [DSP], held a meeting at the First 
House of Representatives Members' Office Building on the evening 
of 14 April. They agreed that if Michio Watanabe, former deputy 
prime minister and foreign minister, leaves the Liberal 
Democratic Party and joins the new administration either as 
deputy prime minister or in some other capacity, then the SDPJ 
and DSP may have to leave the coalition. 
  According to senior DSP officials, Akira Yamagishi, chairman 
of the Japanese Trade Union Confederation [Rengo], also supports 
Murayama and Ouchi's position. 
  It is believed Murayama and Ouchi's coming out with such a 
position is timed to warn Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] and 
Komeito against cooperating with Watanabe, and to change the 
composition of the coalition by dropping Sakigake [Harbinger]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

