Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 April 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Mongolia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Adverse Impact of Government Resignation Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Adverse Impact of Government Resignation Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504182394 Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME in English 1420 GMT 15 Apr 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1504182394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ulaanbaatar, April 15 (OANA-MONTSAME) -- The 
resignation of the government might lead to a slowing down of 
the economic reforming pace. This was said over the national 
television by the chairman of the National Development 
Department under the Prime Minister C. Ulaan. He goes on to say 
that the political hunger strike is quite an ordinary event in a 
democratic society. But the demands referring to resignation of 
the government at the present time when the country is entering 
the decisive year of economic reforms and the government is 
doing its best in order to implement the programme of action for 
1994 approved by the parliament is fraught with adverse 
aftermaths. 
  Especially at the given moment when there is becoming 
transparent a tendency toward a stabilizing of macroeconomic 
showings, it is ackowledged by the international financial and 
economic establishments the government's fulfilling of its 
obligations undertaken, are being developed the joint programmes 
in the fuel and power industry and for developing the 
infrastructure. The transition process in Mongolia is being 
considered as an example of reforming a society. 
  In today's conditions a forming of a new government and 
adopting of its new programme would turn out to be a useless 
waste of time. The political unstableness might cause to a loss 
of confidence in our country on the part of the world community. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-6116 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas074__a94048" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-074-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 April 1994 </DATE1>

