<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Not To Sign Accord on Creation of WTO </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo Not To Sign Accord on Creation of WTO </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504095094 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 14 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 9--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1504095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] It was learned on 13 April that Japan will not sign 
the accord on establishment of the World Trade Organization 
(WTO) at the ministerial talks of the multilateral trade 
negotiations (the Uruguay Round) which are being held in 
Marrakech, Morocco. 
  The government has decided that Japan will sign the final 
agreement document of the Uruguay Round, but will not sign the 
accord on the creation of the WTO out of consideration for the 
ruling Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] which is still 
opposed to the opening up of the Japanese rice market and out of 
the need for Japan to avoid signing the accord before the Diet 
begins deliberating it for approval. The decision shows how 
fragile the coalition government is. 
  In the case of an ordinary treaty, the government signs the 
treaty and each signatory to the treaty ratifies it after 
obtaining approval from the parliament. The WTO accord, made up 
of 18 agreements, which is high on the agenda of the Marrakech 
ministerial talks, is to follow that procedure. 
  The final agreement document, which Japan will sign, is 
merely a piece of paper. It confirms that "the accord on the 
creation of the WTO is a sum of the results of negotiations at 
the Uruguay Round" and makes it mandatory for each signatory to 
submit the accord to its parliament and the accord will take 
effect on 1 January 1995. Therefore, Japan's refusal to sign the 
accord will have no specific impact on it unless the Diet 
refuses to approve it in its autumn session. Japan has attached 
importance to multilateral treaties and its refusal to sign the 
accord is "regrettable," (says a government source). 
  Like Japan, the United States will sign the final agreement 
document, but will not sign the accord because the U.S. 
administration has yet to obtain approval from Congress on 
individual agreements including an agreement on lowering 
tariffs. The European Union (EU) will sign the accord. However, 
the EU member nations are feuding over which side should have 
the authority to sign the accord -- the European Commission or 
member nations. Their dispute is still pending in the European 
Court. 
  Japan, the United States, and Europe have been at a loss 
over 
how to deal with the accord and this confusion shows that 
agreements hammered out at the Uruguay Round are the outcome of 
domestic compromises of each negotiating nation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-6125 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas074__a94002" </HT>


