<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Need To Resume Framework Talks With U.S. Cited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Need To Resume Framework Talks With U.S. Cited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404142694 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 14 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1404142694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kunihiko Saito, administrative vice minister of 
foreign affairs, gave a lecture in Chiba City on 13 April and 
commented on the meeting between Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata 
and U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor scheduled in 
Marrakech, Morocco, on 15 April. He said: "We have absolutely 
no way of knowing whether an agreement can be reached there on a 
resumption of the (Japan-U.S.) framework trade talks. The issue 
may not be settled so easily, particularly because of the 
current political situation in Japan." He thus indicated it 
could be difficult to break the ice in resuming the deadlocked 
framework trade talks. 
  Saito then added: "In the past, mutual interests (between 
Japan and the United States) on security matters have covered up 
bilateral trade friction, but it is unlikely that such a 
situation would continue (in the future). Unless Japan tries 
harder, bilateral relations will worsen, contrary to what has 
happened in the past." He thus stressed the need for Japan to 
actively work toward breaking the deadlock. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

