<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation Meets Hata on U.S. Helicopter Crash </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delegation Meets Hata on U.S. Helicopter Crash </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304140094 Naha OKINAWA TIMES in Japanese 13 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1304140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha OKINAWA TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo -- On 12 April, a delegation led by Ginowan 
Mayor Seiken Tobaru called at the Foreign Ministry and the 
Defense Facilities Administration Agency [DFAA] to meet Tsutomu 
Hata, the foreign minister, and Eisuke Tsuruta, DFAA Chief 
Facilities Coordination Officer. 
  In reaction to a recent helicopter crash on Futenma Marine 
Corps Air Station [MCAS], the mayor strongly urged the 
disclosure of the investigation reports and an early reversion 
of Futenma MCAS, stressing "accidents happen repeatedly because 
U.S. bases are there." In reply, Foreign Minister Hata said: 
"We really understand Okinawan people's feelings. To ease the 
people's uneasy feelings, we would like to continue our efforts 
to meet their demands." 
  In addition to the mayor, the Ginowan delegation included 
municipal assembly Speaker Shunshin Nakamura, Chairman Seiei 
Chinen, and Vice Chairman Shinsho Chibana of the municipal 
assembly special committee on U.S. base problems. Delegation 
members strongly protested the accident, saying: "U.S. Forces 
are continuing military exercises as if they pay no regard to 
Okinawan people's anger at repeated accidents. The Japanese 
Government must bend constant efforts to reversion of U.S. 
bases." They then petitioned for the disclosure of 
investigation reports, an immediate halt to flight training in 
residential areas, and the early reversion of Futenma MCAS. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

