<H3> <TI>   Ozawa Criticizes Takemura on Selecting Premier </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ozawa Criticizes Takemura on Selecting Premier </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504045694 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 15 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1504045694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 14 April Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] Answering correspondents' questions at the Diet 
building on 14 April, Ichiro Ozawa, secretary general of 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] stated: "The moment of decision 
is fast approaching." He indicated that if Chief Cabinet 
Secretary Masayoshi Takemura, head of Sakigake [Harbinger], 
insists on deciding on the new prime minister at a meeting of 
leaders of the coalition parties, he would ask the coalition 
representatives meeting to enter substantial discussions on the 
succession issue without Sakigake. 
  At the end of the representatives meeting on the morning of 
14 April, Ozawa expressed displeasure at the conflict in the 
ruling coalition parties over the venue of discussions to select 
the new prime minister. He stated: "There has been no progress 
at all. We cannot afford to be dilly-dallying forever." 
Concerning the suggestion that the issue be taken up at a joint 
meeting of party leaders and representatives, Ozawa explained: 
"I am not the one opposed to this. Takemura is the problem." 
He criticized Takemura in strong terms, saying "(he) says we 
have to start everything from scratch, including the coalition." 
  With regard to the Social Democratic Party of Japan and the 
Democratic Socialist Party, Ozawa wanted them to take an 
explicit position on whether they want to undertake discussions 
at the party leaders' meeting or at the representatives' 
meeting. He said: "They should talk within their own parties 
whether they want to do things the Sakigake way." 

</TEXT>

