<H3> <TI>   IDC Expands Information Systems Division </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IDC Expands Information Systems Division </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0123A Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 Apr 94 p 
31--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0123A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] IDC To Double Systems Engineering Staff in 
Information Systems Division by Fiscal Yearend by Hiring Mostly 
Experienced Applicants 
  International Digital Communications (IDC) a new telegraph 
and telephone company engaged in international communications, 
headquartered in Daito ward, Tokyo and headed by Kento Orihata, 
will double its systems engineering staff in its Information 
Systems Division during fiscal year 1994. Additionally, this 
development will evolve into the active assignment of the 
division to projects designed to develop new types of services. 
The company will beef up its services development capabilities 
as a way to better compete with rival Kokusai Denshin Denwa 
(KDD). 
  As of 1 March, IDC had a total of 530 employees, of which 38 
were assigned to the Information Systems Division. That number 
will be increased to about 70 in fiscal year 1994. Recruiting 
will focus primarily on experienced applicants, but will also 
include some newly graduated applicants. 
  IDC formerly assigned most of its new services development 
projects to two activities known as "Services Development 
Promotion Section" and "Business Promotion Division." The 
"Information System Division" specialized in projects in the 
administrative area such as the design and operation of billing 
systems and late-payment follow-up systems. However, now that 
communications services have become sophisticated and 
complicated and billing formats will change drastically, IDC 
seeks to enhance developmental efficiency by involving the 
Information Services Division from the early stages of services 
development work. 

</TEXT>

