<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Insurers To Underwrite Satellites </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Insurers To Underwrite Satellites </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1804082294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1804082294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Ministry of Finance will open the underwriting 
of nonlife insurance for artificial satellites to foreign 
insurance companies not holding a Japanese license as early as 
before the end of 1994. The opening of satellite insurance to 
foreign companies has been announced in light of an agreement at 
the GATT Uruguay Round, and will be implemented as soon as the 
Uruguay Round accord is ratified. As to insurance for 
oceangoing vessels and aircraft, the ban on foreign 
participation will be lifted in fiscal 1995, together with the 
reform of the insurance industry, because this requires 
amendments in the relevant laws. 
  The underwriting of insurance by foreign insurers is known 
as 
a "cross-border transaction." This has not been allowed for 
insurance companies not holding a license to operate in Japan, 
except for international cargo and a limited number of other 
items. Due to strong demands to open the market from Western 
nations, the opening of insurance for oceangoing vessels and 
aircraft has been included in the "outline of external economic 
policy reform" announced on 29 March, apart from the Uruguay 
Round agreement. Implementation of this policy in artificial 
satellites is being frontloaded because this does not require 
any legal amendment. 
  Insurance fees for artificial satellites sometimes cost 
several billion yen due to the high risk of failure in launching 
satellites. In Japan, when the National Space Development Agency 
launches its satellites, Japanese nonlife insurers usually 
underwrite insurance jointly, and reinsure with foreign 
insurers. By opening the market to foreign companies, foreign 
reinsurers can now underwrite insurance directly. 
  With regard to ships and aircraft, the selling of insurance 
policies is prohibited for foreign insurers not holding a 
Japanese license under the "Foreign Insurance Companies Law." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

