<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Industry Forum Closes Conference 15 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nuclear Industry Forum Closes Conference 15 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504145794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1425 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1504145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hiroshima, April 15 KYODO -- The Japan Atomic 
Industrial Forum ended Friday [15 April] a three-day conference 
in Hiroshima, the world's first atom-bombed city, with a 
declaration affirming its opposition to nuclear weapons. 
  On the final day, delegates debated the development of 
nuclear energy in the Asian region and the effects of 
radioactivity. 
  A declaration issued at the closing affirmed the delegates' 
opposition to nuclear weapons. It also called for continued 
efforts by countries involved in dismantling nuclear weapons and 
the development of research into technology aimed at making the 
peaceful use of nuclear energy safer. 
  At a news conference after the conference, Takashi Mukaibo, 
chairman of the forum that promotes peaceful use of atomic 
energy, said the group came to Hiroshima "to learn." About 
1,500 atomic power specialists from Japan and abroad took part 
in the 27th annual conference. 
  Hans Blix, director general of the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA), told delegates the IAEA will hold a 
special meeting on April 21 and 22 in Vienna to discuss the 
Chernobyl nuclear reactors in Ukraine. Chernobyl was the scene 
of one of the world's most serious nuclear accidents in 1986. 
  Antinuclear activists protested the gathering around the 
conference hall in central Hiroshima. 
  Next year marks the 50th anniversary of the atomic bombing 
during the closing days of World War II. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

