<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Press Reports on Fighting in Pailin Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Press Reports on Fighting in Pailin Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Battlefield Report: 14-15 Apr </H4>

<F P=102> BK1704090694 (Clandestine) Voice of the Great National Union 
Front of Cambodia in Cambodian 2330 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1704090694 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Voice of the Great National Union 
Front of Cambodia </F>

<F P=105>  Cambodian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The following is a report on the Pailin battlefield 
situation between 14 and 15 April 1994: 
  1. On 14 April, the National Army of Democratic Kampuchea 
attacked the two-headed government troops at Toek S'am adjoining 
Pailin. In the fighting from 0700 to 1800, we destroyed a T-54 
tank and a military truck and we killed 17 enemy soldiers and 
wounded many others. The remaining troops were forced to 
retreat for their lives to Stoeng Kanh. 
  2. On 15 April, we intercepted a group of transport forces 
on the road linking [word indistinct] and Pailin, killing 15 
enemy soldiers and wounding 12 others. The remaining troops 
were forced to retreat behind their lines. 
  3. Those in the Pailin town now are complaining about the 
shortage of rice, [word indistinct], and medicine. Wounded or 
killed soldiers are found everywhere. And roads are blocked 
[words indistinct]. The situation so far is that the invading 
forces have been routed extensively. 
  4. Puppet leaders, like Fifth Military Region Commander Hul 
Savoan and Battambang Province Commander Manh Sophat, have 
already run away from their troops, leaving their subordinates 
to die in Pailin. As for the remaining 200 (Dac Cong) 
Vietnamese soldiers at Phnum Yat, they are also prepared to beat 
a hasty retreat. Since Pailin has completely been surrounded, 
they can only run away through the bamboo-covered jungles. 
Nevertheless, they will be killed by stepping on land mines or 
lose their way and become foxes' or lizards' prey. 

</TEXT>

