<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inspections Linked to Team Spirit Suspension </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Inspections Linked to Team Spirit Suspension </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1704061294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0600 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1704061294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 17 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and the 
United States have decided to agree on suspending their joint 
military exercise "Team Spirit '94" and holding a third round of 
U.S.-North Korean high-level talks if Pyongyang lets additional 
IAEA [International Atomic Energy Agency] inspections of its 
nuclear facilities be successfully concluded, YONHAP learned on 
Sunday [17 April]. 
  "The April 1 statement by the U.N. Security Council 
president 
on the North Korean nuclear problem reaffirmed that the 
U.S.-North Korean agreement reached on Feb. 25 in New York was 
still effective," a high-ranking government official said. "In 
view of this development, Seoul and Washington share the 
position that further U.S.-North Korean talks and suspension of 
the annual military drill are linked to more inspections by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency." 
  Robert Gallucci, U.S. assistant secretary of State for 
political and military affairs, and Kim Sam-hun, ambassador for 
nuclear issue, are expected to reiterate their position when 
they hold a meeting here Monday [18 April]. 
  Regarding Team Spirit in particular, U.S. Defense Secretary 
William Perry, who will soon to visit South Korea, and his South 
Korean counterpart are expected to agree that the military 
maneuver will be suspended only after they get hard evidence 
that North Korea did not divert nuclear materials to making 
weapons. 
  "Dropping the demand for inter-Korean special envoy exchange 
is part of the preconditions set in the New York agreement," the 
official said. "The remaining conditions still hold good." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

