<DOCNO> FBIS4-6188 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas075_d_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Emphasizes U.S. Alliance to Bush </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Emphasizes U.S. Alliance to Bush </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1604071294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0706 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1604071294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 16 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam, 
accusing North Korea of taking every opportunity to own nuclear 
weapons Saturday, stressed close South Korea-U.S. cooperation 
and international coordination in resolving the problem. 
  Meeting former U.S. President George Bush on a visit here, 
Kim said the U.N. Security Council has to act if transparency 
is not guaranteed on North Korea's nuclear program, spokesman 
Chu Ton-Sik said. 
  Bush came to Seoul to attend the 43rd annual conference of 
the Pacific-Asia Travel Association (PATA). 
  Bush agreed that the two countries must maintain firm 
alliance in dealing with the North Korean situation. He warned 
they should not be fooled by North Korea's attempt to break the 
two countries apart during North Korea-U.S. dialogue, Chu said. 
  Bush commented that he saw the tension on the Korean 
peninsula was not as tense as he had thought when he was in the 
United States. 
  Kim accused "irresponsible" people of exaggerating the 
situation, Chu said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

